    <segment id="1" parent="28" relname="span">
Seffah, Kecceci and Donyaee present a very interesting paper on an engineering 
software model that integrates human computer interface principles into its design.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="18" relname="concession"> The 
authors convey that HCI has developed good models for specifying or measuring 
usability</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="21" relname="span"> but these models are weak in the integration within the software engineering 
models.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="22" relname="span"> The authors are suggesting that a relationship should exist between 
characteristics of software and their measurable attributes. (Seffah, 2001)</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="20" relname="span">


	The authors of this paper propose a model called Quality in Use Integrated 
Map (QUIM).</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="23" relname="span"> QUIM defines quality of usage in relationship to end users perspective 
of &quot;did this software produce a quality product&quot;.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration"> It is clearly asking &quot;what have you done 
for me?&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="24" relname="span">  QUIM is an open model</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="16" relname="volitional-cause"> because it considers cause/effect relationships between 
the user and developer.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="26" relname="span">

	In conclusion, the paper outlines the similarities and differences, and 
limitations of a variety models used for measuring usability within HCI and engineering.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="solutionhood"> 
They suggest QUIM as a solution.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="32" relname="span"> The intent is to present a simple, low risk and cost 
effective model that can be used to measure usability.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="33" relname="span">

	This paper goes into quite of bit detail on the QUIM model.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="elaboration"> It presents a 
rational for the model and outlines the methodology and structure.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="31" relname="span"> The thing that I found 
interesting about QUIM is the integration of HCI and engineering.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="19" relname="concession"> There can be many 
models of HCI applied to a software project</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="30" relname="span"> but without the integration of engineering 
into these exercises the outcomes will be limited to partial success.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="29" relname="span"> As a rule engineers 
do not interact a great deal wit users.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="solutionhood"> This would certainly facilitate some very productive 
interaction.</segment>
